{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584742"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:55:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14794"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14794"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.06,0.16,0.06,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7485"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75111"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7485"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14794"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60619"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"5092"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18313"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21692"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75111"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFolic acid (vitamin B9) is an essential nutrient obtained through diet or supplementation. Before it can participate in cellular processes, folic acid must undergo enzymatic conversion to become biologically active.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the initial step in folic acid metabolism?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct incorporation into DNA synthesis","Formation of a vitamin B12 complex","Conversion to methylfolate","Addition of glutamate residues","Reduction to tetrahydrofolate by dihydrofolate reductase"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe initial and essential first step in folic acid metabolism is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduction to tetrahydrofolate by dihydrofolate reductase\u003C/strong\u003E. This creates the active form that can participate in one-carbon transfer reactions necessary for DNA synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect incorporation into DNA synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E cannot occur as folic acid must first be converted to its active form\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of a vitamin B12 complex\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect - while B12 and folate metabolism are linked, they do not form a complex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConversion to methylfolate\u003C/strong\u003E occurs after tetrahydrofolate formation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddition of glutamate residues\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the activation pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce converted to tetrahydrofolate, folate can participate in one-carbon transfer reactions essential for purine and thymidine synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Folic acid must be converted to tetrahydrofolate by dihydrofolate reductase to become biologically active","Tetrahydrofolate is essential for DNA synthesis through its role in purine and thymidine synthesis","Dietary folate is found in green leafy vegetables, legumes and fortified cereals"],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60619"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14794"}},"stemMedia":{"data":